<Base
  title="Isotrace · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="Behavioral path tracing in LLMs via synthetic concept labeling."
  toc={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Localization · parked diagnostic for the modality program
    </div>
    <h1>Isotrace</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      Behavioral path-tracing: which linguistic operation actually carried the inference.
    </p>

    <h2>Problem</h2>
    <p>
      Certification says <em>whether</em> the licensing structure is load-bearing, not <em>which
      part</em> of it carried the inference. Multi-hop benchmarks have the same gap: they tell us
      whether a model got the final answer right, but not which reasoning path it used — a correct
      answer may come from executing the full chain, or from a shortcut that points to the same
      answer. Isotrace is the localization diagnostic that closes that gap; on the modality program
      its target is which linguistic operation (which hop, which encoding) actually did the work.
    </p>

    <p>
      Isotrace is a <strong>behavioral path-tracing protocol</strong>. It does not directly observe
      internal reasoning. Instead, it designs tasks where distinct hypothesized paths produce
      distinct observable labels.
    </p>

    <h2>Core idea</h2>
    <p>
      Encode path information into the output itself. Use fictional concepts and path-encoding
      naming rules, so that the final output name records which reasoning hops were executed.
    </p>

    <h2>Isotope analogy</h2>
    <p>
      In chemistry, isotope tracing labels molecules and observes where the label ends up, without
      opening the reaction vessel. Isotrace does the same for LLM reasoning: the concept name acts
      as the label, reasoning hops transform the label, and the final output reveals the path.
    </p>

    <IsotraceFigure />

    <h2>Core mechanism</h2>
    <h3>Synthetic concepts</h3>
    <p>
      Use fictional names such as <code>Zorb</code>, <code>Veln</code>, and <code>Quasp</code> to
      reduce contamination from prior world knowledge.
    </p>

    <h3>Path-encoding naming rules</h3>
    <pre><code>Rule 1: A Zorb that satisfies condition X is called Zorb-α.
Rule 2: A Zorb-α that satisfies condition Y is called Zorb-α-prime.
Rule 3: A Zorb-α-prime that satisfies condition Z is called Zorb-α-prime-Ω.</code></pre>

    <h3>Output interpretation</h3>
    <pre><code>Zorb                 -> no hop executed / chain broken at hop 1
Zorb-α               -> hop 1 completed, chain broke before hop 2
Zorb-α-prime         -> hops 1-2 completed, chain broke before hop 3
Zorb-α-prime-Ω       -> full chain executed</code></pre>

    <h2>Hop-level interventions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hop deletion:</strong> remove rule <code>k</code> to test whether hop <code>k</code> is genuinely load-bearing or whether the model bridges over it.</li>
      <li><strong>Shortcut injection:</strong> introduce a spurious cue at hop <code>k</code> to test whether the model shortcut-replaces that hop.</li>
      <li><strong>Order scrambling:</strong> present rules out of order to distinguish logical structure use from positional heuristics.</li>
      <li><strong>Label perturbation:</strong> keep the logical structure fixed but swap the surface labels, to distinguish genuine path-following from surface instruction-following.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Relationship to the verdict method</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Stable Is Not Grounded (certify):</strong> binary certification. Is the licensing structure counterfactually load-bearing?</li>
      <li><strong>Isotrace (localize):</strong> path-level localization. Which hop was used, bypassed, or shortcut-replaced?</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Key methodological risk</h2>
    <p>
      The central confound is instruction-following or rule-copying. A model may output the correct
      transformed name not because it verified the condition for that hop, but because it copied the
      naming pattern from the prompt. For example, if the prompt says "a Zorb satisfying X is called
      Zorb-α," the model might output <code>Zorb-α</code> without checking whether this particular
      Zorb satisfies X.
    </p>

    <h2>Diagnostic fix</h2>
    <p>
      Use adversarial contrast pairs with the same naming rules but different underlying facts.
    </p>

    <pre><code>Prompt A:
Same rules.
This Zorb satisfies X.
Correct output: Zorb-α.

Prompt B:
Same rules.
This Zorb does not satisfy X.
Correct output: Zorb.</code></pre>

    <p>
      A rule-copying model will tend to output the same transformed name in both prompts. A model
      that actually applies the rule should output different names. This contrast is central: it
      turns the main weakness of the method into a falsifiable test.
    </p>

    <h2>Linguistic instantiation</h2>
    <p>
      The synthetic names above are a contamination control, not the end goal. The direction is to
      make the <strong>hops linguistic</strong>: a path becomes a chain of linguistic inferences
      (e.g. agreement → binding → scope, or successive morphological derivations), so the output
      label records which <em>linguistic level</em> the model's reasoning actually executed — which
      is exactly the "where" the program needs.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/research/mini-causal-models">MiniCausalLang</a> then supplies the items as
      <strong>typological minimal pairs</strong>: one causal graph re-encoded by morphology, word
      order, or context. Isotrace traces which surface encoding carried the inference — turning the
      contamination-control design into a typological one, and tying Isotrace directly to the
      <a href="/research/typological-grounding">typological-grounding</a> frontier.
    </p>

    <h2>Status</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Conceptual and early methodological stage.</li>
      <li>Core analogy established.</li>
      <li>Basic mechanism designed.</li>
      <li>Relationship to the certification method and the modality program defined.</li>
      <li>Next milestone: a 3-hop pilot experiment with clean chain, hop deletion, shortcut-at-hop-k, order scrambling, label perturbation, and adversarial rule-copying controls.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The claim is intentionally modest. Isotrace does not claim to trace the model's real reasoning
      process directly. It gives a behavioral design in which competing path hypotheses have
      different observable consequences.
    </p>

    <hr/>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">An interactive path-label pilot will live here once the experiment is stable.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
